# Expert tier tasks — 5 tasks
# Format: task_name|prompt
# Each prompt instructs the agent to work in /tmp/training-TASKNAME/, init a Go module,
# write implementation in main package, include _test.go, and run go test ./... to verify.

timeseries-store|Work in /tmp/training-timeseries/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/timeseries). Write store.go in package main implementing an in-memory time-series store: type Store with Write(key string, ts int64, value float64), Query(key string, from, to int64) []Point where Point is {TS int64; Value float64} sorted ascending by TS. Concurrent reads and writes must be safe. Use per-key RWMutex or segment locking. Write store_test.go with correctness tests (boundary-inclusive query, overlapping writes, unknown key returns empty) and a concurrent stress test: 10 writers + 10 readers running for 200ms. Run go test -race ./... and report. Acceptance: -race clean, correct query boundaries.

promise|Work in /tmp/training-promise/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/promise). Write promise.go in package main implementing: type Promise[T any] representing an async computation. New(func() (T, error)) *Promise[T] starts the computation in a goroutine. Then(func(T) (T, error)) *Promise[T] chains on success. Catch(func(error) (T, error)) *Promise[T] handles errors. Await() (T, error) blocks for result. Write promise_test.go testing: successful chain of 3 .Then calls, error propagation halts the chain and Catch recovers, concurrent Await from multiple goroutines returns same result. Run go test -race ./... and report. Acceptance: -race clean, all chain semantics correct.

pubsub-broker|Work in /tmp/training-pubsub/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/pubsub). Write broker.go in package main implementing a minimal pub/sub broker: type Broker with Subscribe(topic string) (<-chan []byte, func()), Publish(topic string, msg []byte) int (returns subscriber count), subscriber lag tracking via Len() int per subscriber channel (buffered, drop policy if full). Write broker_test.go with: basic pub/sub, multiple subscribers, unsubscribe cleans up, concurrent publish stress test (100 goroutines * 1000 msgs), lag counter increments on dropped messages. Run go test -race ./... and report. Acceptance: -race clean, no goroutine leak after unsubscribe.

expression-parser|Work in /tmp/training-exprparser/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/exprparser). Write parser.go in package main implementing a recursive-descent parser for arithmetic expressions: +, -, *, /, parentheses, integer literals, and named variables (identifiers). Produce an AST with node types: NumberNode, VarNode, BinOpNode. Write eval.go with Eval(node Node, vars map[string]float64) (float64, error). Write parser_test.go with table tests: "1+2*3"->7, "(1+2)*3"->9, "x*2" with x=5 ->10, division by zero returns error, unknown variable returns error. Run go test ./... and report. Acceptance: operator precedence correct, all 5+ cases pass.

constant-folding|Work in /tmp/training-constfold/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/constfold). Reuse the AST from the expression parser (copy parser.go and eval.go from /tmp/training-exprparser/ if available, or rewrite minimal versions). Write fold.go in package main implementing: func ConstFold(node Node) Node — an SSA-style constant folding pass that replaces BinOpNode where both children are NumberNode with a single NumberNode of the computed value. Example: (1+2)*x folds to 3*x. Write fold_test.go with table tests: "1+2*3" folds entirely to 9, "(4/2)+x" folds to 2+x, "x+y" is unchanged. Verify folded ASTs evaluate identically to unfolded ones. Run go test ./... and report. Acceptance: all fold tests pass, evaluation equivalence verified.
